Do NOT write SQL. Produce a logical plan that another step will translate into SQL.

Work through the analytical grammar:
  1. intent — classify the question's analytical archetype.
  2. measures — what gets aggregated (expressions like SUM(payment.amount) AS revenue); empty for a pure lookup.
  3. grain — what one row of the fact/base table represents (e.g. "one row per payment"). This is the anchor for fan-out.
  4. dimensions — the columns to break down / GROUP BY.
  5. filters — the scope (WHERE conditions); time_grain for any date bucketing/range.
  6. derived — ranking, share-of-total, or period-over-period calcs (these become window functions).
  7. having / order_by / limit.
  8. join_path — how to get from the fact table to the dimensions, with keys.
  9. fan_out_risk — CRUCIAL: if aggregating a measure across a one-to-many or many-to-many join would double-count it, say so and prescribe the fix (pre-aggregate the measure in a CTE at its own grain first, or COUNT(DISTINCT)). Otherwise "none".
  10. assumptions — anything you assumed, especially metric definitions (e.g. "revenue := SUM(payment.amount)").

Use only tables/columns from the provided schema. Reference concrete column names.
